---
description: Shell and command execution mechanics
globs: **/*
alwaysApply: true
---

File editing: Read the current state of a file immediately before editing it. The user may have made changes since the file was last read, and edits should reflect the actual current content.

Tools: Use bash and zsh compatible commands, one step at a time. Prefer vim or nvim for editing. For repo access use: gh repo clone <owner>/<repo> -- --depth 1

Dates: Determine the current year dynamically using: date +"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S %Z"

Make sure to mind the shell actively in use, as bash quoting does not work in zsh.

Cross-system compatibility: Use `$EPOCHSECONDS` for Unix timestamps and zsh builtins or `printf` for date and file metadata formatting. This machine has both BSD and GNU variants of `stat` and `date` installed alongside each other (`gstat`, `gdate`), so prefer builtins that sidestep that ambiguity entirely.

SSH remote commands: When passing a command to `ssh host <command>`, quote the entire remote command string in single quotes (e.g. `ssh host 'somecommand --flag=value[index]'`) so that the local zsh shell passes the argument verbatim without glob expansion.
For anything more complex than a single command, write the logic to a temp file via `mktemp`, `scp` it to the host, execute it there, and clean up afterward.

Complex commands: For anything more complex than a single command locally, write the logic to a temp file via `mktemp`, execute it, and clean up afterward.
